I notice that the `Input` component is being controlled by the `Controller` component from `react-hook-form`. However, in the `Input` component, the `onChange` prop is not actually being used to capture user input. Instead, the `defaultValue` prop is being used to set the initial input value.

This can cause issues with the required validation if the `defaultValue` prop is set to an empty string. In that case, the form will submit even if the input field is empty because the input field already has a value (empty string). To fix this issue, you can set the `defaultValue` prop to `undefined` or `null`.

Here's an updated `Input` component that passes the `onChange` prop to the `input` element:

```jsx
import { FormField } from '../FormField';
import styles from './styles.module.css';

const Input = ({
  label,
  type = 'text',
  id,
  className,
  value,
  defaultValue,
  onChange,
  error,
}) => {
  return (
    <FormField error={error}>
      <div className={styles.inputWrapper}>
        {label && (
          <label
            htmlFor={id}
            className={styles.inputLabel}
            style={{ marginBottom: 0 }}
          >
            {label}
          </label>
        )}
        <input
          type={type}
          className={`form-control morphfield ${styles.input} ${className}`}
          id={id}
          aria-describedby="emailHelp"
          defaultValue={defaultValue}
          value={value}
          onChange={onChange}
        />
      </div>
    </FormField>
  );
};

export { Input };
```

In the updated `Input` component, the `onChange` prop is passed to the `input` element instead of the `defaultValue` prop. Also, the `defaultValue` prop is unchanged if no initial value is provided.

I hope this helps resolve the issue. Let me know if there's anything else I can help you with.

